Second:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Can anyone tell me they've lost a child and wouldn't feel anything at all when being reminded of such a loss, reguardless of roleplay?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I'm sorry but that's way to much personal information about someone I dont really know.  I play everquest to get away from the messy details of real life.  I think its tragic for that to happen to anyone, but I gotta say... It's none of our buisness so why is it being shoved in our faces?  No one can know everything thats happened to another person, and its not fair or realistic to expect people to walk on eggshells.<br>
<br>
You talk about the line between accetable and unaccetable roleplay... well how the hell are people suppose to draw that line when you wish it based on VERY personal experiances that, generally, people dont share with strangers?<br>
<br>
The person that made the comment had no idea of this persons background or any event like this, and I really think its shitty for someone to bring up such personal information in defense of a thread on a fucking message board.  Stuff like this doesnt belong anywhere NEAR EQ.  I tell you what, if you were my RL friend and brought up something so personal on a message board, we'd have some harsh words.<br>
<br>
Shame on you for using something like that as emotional leverage.  You should be ashamde of yourself.  If she was upset by it she could have spoken up herself, and unless she appointed you her defender, I'd say your out of line.  I dont WANT to be involved in people's personal lives, if something traumatic is brought up the mature thing to do is to say &quot;ooc im sorry that's enough, can't rp this anymore&quot; and leave it at that.<br>
<br>
Any decent person hearing that, (like most of the people who have spoken on this thread) would appologize and offer some comfort.  That's called being mature.  You can't expect to never have tragic events brought to memory accidentally and I think part of coping with them is understanding that.<br>
<br>
~PoVabris<br>
<br>
